english:
  title: A Separate Memorial
  author: Kim Gu
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The righteousness between ruler and subject lies in merciful forbearance that does not cast away. The devotion of a minister or son must speak plainly without concealment.

    Recently when the envoy returned, I received several edicts to convey. Among them, the matter of establishing relay stations—though our people are weakened and cannot truly bear it, such measures were set in place to comfort them. The wayhouses now stretch unbroken even to the northern frontier, as the tributary envoys have witnessed. The remaining proclamations of many kinds I too wished to report in due season, yet I hesitate.

    For our surviving people, only now emerging from desolation into utmost compassion, dwelt like beasts in wild thickets before gathering together. Under their humble thatched shelters they breathe like fish in the wheel-ruts of water. Should we count their numbers at such a time, I fear these simple folk, having known calamity, will grow only more anxious, clouded in the law's meaning. I beseech you to turn your abundant care toward them gently, allowing their hearts to find rest and their recovery to be assured.

    Moreover, regarding the mobilizing of troops and transport of provisions—after the warfare ceased, famine and plague have followed in succession. Of the surviving people, barely two or three remain of every hundred. Of the harvest from the land, eight or nine of every ten are gone. The old and young lack provision; how then can we support the six armies? Morning and evening our people struggle to eat; how can they bear to sustain distant expeditions a thousand leagues away?

    If we forget the poverty of our strength and merely press forward under imperial command, speaking no truth but forcing compliance, and later fail to meet the deadline—what answer can I give? I would only heap blame upon myself and fear betraying the grace of Heaven that sustains us. Advance and retreat alike seem impossible. Trembling in confusion, I know not what to do.

    I humbly beg your compassion. Forgive the people's condition and do not press them harshly. Grant us your sovereign mercy and moderate your demands according to circumstances. Leave us yet outside the strictest ordinances, that we may exist within the circle of your utmost benevolence. Wait until our people possess stable livelihoods and the fields are gradually reclaimed. Then, when they obey your commands, you shall forever display the virtue of cherishing life.
  footnotes:
    - 'Relay stations (置郵事): A system for government communication and official travel that required local support.'
    - 'Six armies (六師): A traditional term for the armed forces.'
    - 'The metaphor of fish in wheel-ruts: A classical image from Zhuangzi representing survival in dire straits through mutual aid.'
    - 'Tributary envoys: Representatives from Ming China who monitored Korean affairs.'
    - 'Stable livelihoods (恒産): A Confucian concept denoting the material security necessary for moral development.'
